				<outline text="Something they don’t teach us in school in my country is that when we pledge allegiance to the flag of the United States of America, we are really pledging allegiance to each other. Because that’s all there is, the people. No dear leader, no state church, just us." type="tweet" created="Mon, 26 Jul 2021 08:43:47 GMT" tweetId="1419579189523591170" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1419579189523591170" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
					<outline text="I think the above would actually make a good Pledge of Allegiance. 

You could drop the first part about not teaching it in school.

&quot;When we pledge allegiance to the flag of...&quot;

It's almost like a blessing. Reincorporation. Back to basics. 

Of the people, etc." type="tweet" created="Mon, 26 Jul 2021 18:21:11 GMT" tweetId="1419724495909228555" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1419724495909228555" inReplyToId="1419579189523591170" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
						<outline text="what's nice about it is that it isn't a race thing, it's what's obviously been true about the US all along, and we've overlooked the contradictions too long. 

how could they say we're pledging allegiance to each other if only some of us have freedom, and only some of us can vote" type="tweet" created="Mon, 26 Jul 2021 18:55:34 GMT" tweetId="1419733149165232131" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1419733149165232131" inReplyToId="1419724495909228555" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
